.\"\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eThe US Army has a lengthy list of requirements. Among them, it wants a handgun with an adjustable grip that can easily fit large or small hands. That way, shooters don't have to adjust their grip mid-fight to operate hard-to-reach buttons or levers. The gun should accommodate sights that make it easier to shoot in low light. It should have a rail on which soldiers can easily attach additional equipment, like infrared pointers. The military also wants a gun that can be equipped with a suppressor, which muffles the sound of gunshots. \u003ca href\u003d\"http://gearscout.militarytimes.com/2015/02/27/beretta-apx-pre-release-walk-through/\"\u003eBeretta intends to enter a new pistol called the APX into the competition\u003c/a\u003e. The new gun is a major engineering departure from the M9. It has a polymer frame like more recent handguns and can meet the Army's other requirements.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eBeretta has publicly complained that \u003ca href\u003d\"http://www.armytimes.com/story/defense/show-daily/ausa/2015/10/14/gun-makers-discuss-offerings-new-army-pistol/73943028/\"\u003ethe government never formally requested efforts to improve its M9\u003c/a\u003e, which the company said is a standard procedure for upgrading platforms. \"If you look at the history... for a variety of weapons, you'll find all along we'll have used spiral development, product improvement. Where was the requirement they notify prime contractor with an opportunity to fix the problem?\" says Howard Yellen, a military adviser for Beretta.\n\n\u003chr\u003e\n\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e \u003csmall\u003e \u003ca href\u003d\"//soylentnews.org/submit.pl?op\u003dviewsub\u0026amp;subid\u003d10219\"\u003eOriginal Submission\u003c/a\u003e \u003c/small\u003e \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href\u003d\"https://soylentnews.org/article.pl?sid\u003d15/10/23/0333256\u0026amp;from\u003drss\"\u003eRead more of this story\u003c/a\u003e at SoylentNews.\u003c/p\u003e","categori